И я поклялся, что если смогу выбраться из родной империи, то первым делом поеду в Венецию, сниму комнату на первом этаже какого-нибудь палаццо, чтобы волны от проходящих лодок плескали в окно, напишу пару элегий, туша сигареты о сырой каменный пол, буду кашлять и пить и на исходе денег вместо билета на поезд куплю маленький браунинг и не сходя с места вышибу себе мозги, не сумев умереть в Венеции от естественных причин.

And I vowed to myself that should I ever get out of my empire, should this eel ever escape the Baltic, the first thing I would do would be to come to Venice, rent a room on the ground floor of some palazzo so that the waves raised by passing boats would splash against my window, write a couple of elegies while extinguishing my cigarettes on the damp stony floor, cough and drink, and, when the money got short, instead of boarding a train, buy myself a little Browning and blow my brains out on the spot, unable to die in Venice of natural causes.

1.because of the lack of land locals bury people in blocks like these, where throughout the years you can put some more relatives inside, or if the rent of this space is over(!), the ashes is just thrown away and it's filled with some other corpses

Jewish people actually seem to be great in spite they didn't want to let me enter the country. I finally made it to Tel Aviv, but my friends didn't because of the ridiculous Israeli laws. Now I have a compulsion to avenge and drink, smoke and eat falafel for three of us.

Keep posting the pretty Rift Valley pictures - alt. 3000m. -one of the most beautiful places I've ever been to. However Nairobi itself is extremely dangerous - even locals beware of going out after sunset because everyone can be robbed even at the daytime; Here is a black market where you can buy a baby; also the matatu drivers (local buses) ran over people and just leave too often - and no one cares.
Surprisingly Nairobi is full of white people whose progenitors settled down there since the colonization so locals don't stare at us all the time like in Tanzania.
Some parts of Kenya can easily pass for Switzerland. So as the prices here are unreasonably high.
I live in Nairobi at my friend's place, right next to the crocodile farm. And the monkeys are hanging all around her backyard and steal the food from the house

I ended up teaching Microsoft word and excel to the 18years olds and it was so.. refreshing. I couldn't ever imagine myself doing smth like that before as my IT knowledge is too basic.  The students didn't really know how to type therefore I felt a bit more confident amidst them.
Now I'm going to Kenya. Peace.
All these guys are from the countries with the direct access to the ocean. But still I'm the one who can swim and refused wearing a life jacket
What surprises me most is that nobody aspires to a higher standard of living here. People are absolutely ok with all the mess around and keep saying "Hakuna matata" in any situation
Obama has never been to Tanzania, but for some reason here is an Obama shop, Obama road, ..so as Malik street.
Most of the buildings that remain the German architecture look like no one could ever live there, but locals have no other options and reside it to such an extent that it turns into sheer slums.
I've bought some items from the local artist' shop and he was so grateful that invited us to see his studio on the backyard that occupied almost a huge block

The island we've visited is probably the only one 'cultured' nice place in Tanzania. So it is entirely turned into a typical resort for the white people with the white-people-prices and attractions. Today I came across the book titled "мент обреченный" by an obscure author on the library-shelf in our hotel, right next to Koran.

Eventually we took a ferry to the island. A sailor's boat costs 5000 Tanzanian shillings (3USD) and a ferry - 50000 (школа экономии не сработала, прости, Кур). But on the ferry l met a guy from NY who established a school and a hospital in Kenya and he happened to go to the same concert of The String Cheese Incident in October.

Yesterday and today we were trying to get on Zanzibar island by the sailor's boats. The boats are tiny and stuffed with tomatoes and fish for the island. No life jackets, furious weather, a few boats drowning every month didn't stop us, but ultimately the sailors discovered that there are some muzungu(white people) in our group and refused 'giving us a ride' as we have more protection from our white countries.

-While selling the dresses and skirts the locals stretch them so as it can fit all African women with incredibly.. voluptuous figures; -I've tried grasshoppers and it tasted disgusting, but it costs a lot because everybody likes it;  -today I've seen a man selling the dead rats, and no one could explain me why

The public transport here is something wonderful. People are jumping into a vehicle right on its way and fetch their kids and bags through the windows. The weather is +34 usually and you're literally  dying inside. Also it seems like here are 3 traffic lights in the whole city and they cause nothing but the unbearable jams. That is why I  usually take a motorbike - it's like a taxi service - I made friends with one guy and he makes me a discount everyday I go to my orphanage

From this point the city looks quite nice and peaceful, but it's suffocatingly polluted and jammed with traffic to the core. I'm getting used to it, but still feel that Russia is so great though. So while going through the culture shock of Russia after the US, Tanzania made me love my country much more.

I feel like I'm too colorful around the others. 

The African perception of time and all kind of problems is super easy and chill, that it takes time for me to adjust to it. The life flows very slowly, being one hour late is totally normal, etc..so as a rushing Russian I tend to hurry everyone up, require people to be better organized, so they started calling me Putin.

Mostly the indigenous are incredibly kind to me, however here are still a certain number of conservative people who keep the offence after the colonization and would never let the white in their house. Anyway, I manage to walk around myself, even travel by the public transport. The life is definitely tough here, but the locals don't really know how it can be, so they are quite happy

This week I was temporarily working at the local orphanage. The kids were so excited to see my camera, so they took these pictures of us. But from the next week I'm supposed to work at the Austrian based orphanage to teach IT and Photoshop haha

The photo with more than 3 persons btw:) We are inside a tiny vehicle adapted by Tanzanians from India. The seating capacity is 3-4, but in comparison to India, no one cares and 10-11 people can stuff it up. 
These are the amazing guys from MC team in aiesec organization (the main executive board thing), mostly I spend time with them.

Well, it's my fifth day  here, and I still haven't seen a white person yet. I live in the intern house full of volunteers all over Africa and hang out in the areas that only locals know. People around always greet me and try to touch. They call me 'muzungu' which means 'a white colonizer', - that's the first word in Swahili that I learned. Today while walking down the ocean shore, we came across the music video filming, and I was asked to participate in a shoot. For some reason they wanted me to come up to the musician and shake his hand.

Ещё я, кстати, получила работу - организовываю задания в интернете для студентов по русскому языку, записываюсь свой голос и т.п. Получается заработать за час больше, чем в кофехаусе за 13-часовой рабочий день.

Продолжая тему о том,что я живу в лесу,хочу зафиксировать,что места эти неимоверно красивые,по территории кампуса ходят  олени, а мы ходим делать домашнее задание на водопады или берег реки, которую вы видите на этой загадочной фотографии. А ещё мне кажется,что в России я тоже начну улыбаться незнакомым людям,и меня там не особо поймут.
